        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Controlling the Desktop Programmatically"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After a vision model identifies which element to interact with, the agent must physically move the cursor and send keystrokes. Python's pyautogui library exposes the full set of low-level input primitives \u2014 mouse movement, clicks, scroll, key presses, hotkeys \u2014 in a cross-platform API that works on macOS, Windows, and Linux (via X11 or xdotool)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Mouse and keyboard action primitives available via pyautogui",
          "title": "Mouse and keyboard control primitives"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mouse Actions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every mouse action takes pixel coordinates in screen space. Always move before clicking \u2014 pyautogui's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "click()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " teleports the cursor by default, which can confuse applications that track hover events. Pass "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "duration"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "moveTo()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to simulate human-like movement."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pyautogui\nimport time\n\n# Safety: move speed makes automation look natural and avoids miss-clicks\npyautogui.PAUSE = 0.05          # 50ms between every pyautogui call\npyautogui.FAILSAFE = True       # move mouse to corner (0,0) to abort\n\ndef click(x: int, y: int, button: str = \"left\") -> None:\n    \"\"\"Smooth move then click. button: 'left', 'right', 'middle'.\"\"\"\n    pyautogui.moveTo(x, y, duration=0.2, tween=pyautogui.easeOutQuad)\n    pyautogui.click(button=button)\n\ndef double_click(x: int, y: int) -> None:\n    pyautogui.moveTo(x, y, duration=0.2)\n    pyautogui.doubleClick()\n\ndef drag(x1: int, y1: int, x2: int, y2: int, duration: float = 0.4) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Click-drag from (x1, y1) to (x2, y2).\"\"\"\n    pyautogui.moveTo(x1, y1, duration=0.2)\n    pyautogui.dragTo(x2, y2, duration=duration, button=\"left\")\n\ndef scroll_at(x: int, y: int, clicks: int) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Scroll at position. Positive clicks = up, negative = down.\"\"\"\n    pyautogui.moveTo(x, y, duration=0.1)\n    pyautogui.scroll(clicks)\n\n# Example: click a Submit button at pixel (312, 420)\nclick(312, 420)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Set "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "pyautogui.FAILSAFE = True"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in every script. It lets you regain control by throwing the cursor to screen corner (0, 0), which raises a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "FailSafeException"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and stops the agent. Without it, a runaway agent is difficult to interrupt."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keyboard Actions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keyboard input has two modes: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "typewrite"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (string \u2192 keystroke sequence) and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "press"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (special key or hotkey). Use typewrite for text fields; use press for control keys, shortcuts, and form submission."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pyautogui\nimport time\n\ndef type_text(text: str, interval: float = 0.04) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Type printable characters with a natural inter-key delay.\n\n    typewrite() only handles ASCII. For Unicode use pyperclip + hotkey.\n    \"\"\"\n    printable = text.encode(\"ascii\", errors=\"replace\").decode()\n    pyautogui.typewrite(printable, interval=interval)\n\ndef type_unicode(text: str) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Type arbitrary Unicode by pasting from clipboard.\"\"\"\n    import pyperclip\n    pyperclip.copy(text)\n    pyautogui.hotkey(\"ctrl\", \"v\")   # or \"cmd\", \"v\" on macOS\n\ndef press_key(key: str) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Press a single key by name.\n\n    Key names: 'enter', 'tab', 'escape', 'backspace', 'delete',\n               'up', 'down', 'left', 'right', 'home', 'end',\n               'pageup', 'pagedown', 'f1'-'f12', 'space', ...\n    \"\"\"\n    pyautogui.press(key)\n\ndef hotkey(*keys: str) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Press a keyboard shortcut. Keys held down in order, released in reverse.\"\"\"\n    pyautogui.hotkey(*keys)\n\n# Common patterns:\ntype_text(\"hello@example.com\")\npress_key(\"tab\")               # move to next field\ntype_text(\"mysecretpassword\")\npress_key(\"enter\")             # submit form\n\nhotkey(\"ctrl\", \"a\")            # select all\nhotkey(\"ctrl\", \"c\")            # copy\nhotkey(\"ctrl\", \"z\")            # undo"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keyboard Navigation as a Fallback"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a click target is too small or ambiguous, keyboard navigation is more reliable. Tab cycles through focusable elements; Enter activates the focused control. This is especially useful for forms where the model has identified the field order but coordinate precision is uncertain."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pyautogui\n\ndef fill_form_by_tab(fields: list[str]) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Fill a form by tabbing between fields, typing each value, then submitting.\n\n    Args:\n        fields: Ordered list of values for each form field.\n                The last element is submitted by pressing Enter.\n    \"\"\"\n    for i, value in enumerate(fields):\n        if value:                          # skip empty fields (still tab past them)\n            type_text(value)\n        if i < len(fields) - 1:\n            pyautogui.press(\"tab\")         # advance to next field\n        else:\n            pyautogui.press(\"enter\")       # submit on last field\n\n# Navigate a modal dialog without relying on coordinates:\n# Tab to \"OK\" button (or \"Cancel\"), then press Enter\ndef dismiss_dialog(confirm: bool = True) -> None:\n    target_key = \"enter\" if confirm else \"escape\"\n    pyautogui.press(target_key)\n\n# Select text inside the currently focused input:\ndef select_field_text() -> None:\n    hotkey(\"ctrl\", \"a\")   # select all text in field"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Building a Unified Input API"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Claude's computer use API defines a typed action schema. Wrapping pyautogui behind a similar schema makes the agent's action loop clean and testable \u2014 the same action dict from the model drives both the real desktop and a mock in tests."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from __future__ import annotations\nfrom typing import Literal, Union\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nimport pyautogui\n\n# --- Action types ---\n\n@dataclass\nclass ClickAction:\n    type: Literal[\"click\"] = \"click\"\n    x: int = 0\n    y: int = 0\n    button: str = \"left\"\n\n@dataclass\nclass TypeAction:\n    type: Literal[\"type\"] = \"type\"\n    text: str = \"\"\n\n@dataclass\nclass KeyAction:\n    type: Literal[\"key\"] = \"key\"\n    key: str = \"\"            # e.g. \"enter\", \"tab\"\n\n@dataclass\nclass HotkeyAction:\n    type: Literal[\"hotkey\"] = \"hotkey\"\n    keys: list[str] = None   # e.g. [\"ctrl\", \"c\"]\n\n@dataclass\nclass ScrollAction:\n    type: Literal[\"scroll\"] = \"scroll\"\n    x: int = 0\n    y: int = 0\n    dy: int = 0              # positive = up, negative = down\n\nAction = Union[ClickAction, TypeAction, KeyAction, HotkeyAction, ScrollAction]\n\n# --- Executor ---\n\ndef execute_action(action: Action) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Dispatch any Action to the appropriate pyautogui call.\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(action, ClickAction):\n        pyautogui.moveTo(action.x, action.y, duration=0.2)\n        pyautogui.click(button=action.button)\n    elif isinstance(action, TypeAction):\n        # Unicode-safe typing via clipboard\n        import pyperclip\n        pyperclip.copy(action.text)\n        pyautogui.hotkey(\"ctrl\", \"v\")\n    elif isinstance(action, KeyAction):\n        pyautogui.press(action.key)\n    elif isinstance(action, HotkeyAction):\n        pyautogui.hotkey(*(action.keys or []))\n    elif isinstance(action, ScrollAction):\n        pyautogui.moveTo(action.x, action.y, duration=0.1)\n        pyautogui.scroll(action.dy)\n    else:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Unknown action type: {type(action)}\")\n\n# --- From model JSON ---\n\ndef action_from_dict(d: dict) -> Action:\n    t = d[\"type\"]\n    if t == \"click\":\n        return ClickAction(x=d[\"x\"], y=d[\"y\"], button=d.get(\"button\", \"left\"))\n    if t == \"type\":\n        return TypeAction(text=d[\"text\"])\n    if t == \"key\":\n        return KeyAction(key=d[\"key\"])\n    if t == \"hotkey\":\n        return HotkeyAction(keys=d[\"keys\"])\n    if t == \"scroll\":\n        return ScrollAction(x=d.get(\"x\", 0), y=d.get(\"y\", 0), dy=d.get(\"dy\", 0))\n    raise ValueError(f\"Unknown action type: {t}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
